    "nickname": "Rubikstein",
    "content": "Very nice idea! My main perplexities are about the test cases.\n\nFirst: does the problem really need so many test cases? They're 11, and it looks like there's a lot of redundancy here (e.g: having three different random instances looks like an overkill). Of course there isn't a \"correct\" amount of tests, but can you shrink it down to 7 or 8 at most?\n\nSecond: usually, each validator instance corresponds to one user-test instance (just with different numbers to prevent hardcoded solutions), but here some validators don't have a correspondence with any test-case. I'm thinking about \"Long-range lightningrod\"/\"Not long enough!\" and \"I can do anything\"/\"I can't do anything\" that test two opposite cases, or \"Blind lightningrod\"/\"Chaos storm\" that don't look similar at all.",
